HelpDataItem.text:
{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f0\fs17 Compiled in Lua Modules:\par
- Lua Socket 2.0.2\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 _G\par
\par
A global variable (not a function) that holds the global environment (that is, _G._G = _G). Lua itself does not use this variable; changing its value does not affect any environment, nor vice-versa. (Use setfenv to change environments.)\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 _VERSION\par
\par
A global variable (not a function) that holds a string containing the current interpreter version. The current contents of this variable is "Lua 5.1".\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 assert (v [, message])\par
\par
Issues an error when the value of its argument v is false (i.e., nil or false); otherwise, returns all its arguments. message is an error message; when absent, it defaults to "assertion failed!"\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 dofile (filename)\par
\par
Opens the named file and executes its contents as a Lua chunk. When called without arguments, dofile executes the contents of the standard input (stdin). Returns all values returned by the chunk. In case of errors, dofile propagates the error to its caller (that is, dofile does not run in protected mode).\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 getfenv ([f])\par
\par
Returns the current environment in use by the function. f can be a Lua function or a number that specifies the function at that stack level: Level 1 is the function calling getfenv. If the given function is not a Lua function, or if f is 0, getfenv returns the global environment. The default for f is 1.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 getmetatable (object)\par
\par
If object does not have a metatable, returns nil. Otherwise, if the object's metatable has a "__metatable" field, returns the associated value. Otherwise, returns the metatable of the given object.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 ipairs (t)\par
\par
Returns three values: an iterator function, the table t, and 0, so that the construction\par
will iterate over the pairs (1,t[1]), (2,t[2]), \'b7\'b7\'b7, up to the first integer key absent from the table.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 loadfile ([filename])\par
\par
Similar to load, but gets the chunk from file filename or from the standard input, if no file name is given.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 pcall (f, arg1, \'b7\'b7\'b7)\par
\par
Calls function f with the given arguments in protected mode. This means that any error inside f is not propagated; instead, pcall catches the error and returns a status code. Its first result is the status code (a boolean), which is true if the call succeeds without errors. In such case, pcall also returns all results from the call, after this first result. In case of any error, pcall returns false plus the error message.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 print (\'b7\'b7\'b7)\par
\par
Receives any number of arguments, and prints their values to stdout, using the tostring function to convert them to strings. print is not intended for formatted output, but only as a quick way to show a value, typically for debugging. For formatted output, use string.format.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 rawequal (v1, v2)\par
\par
Checks whether v1 is equal to v2, without invoking any metamethod. Returns a boolean.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 rawget (table, index)\par
\par
Gets the real value of table[index], without invoking any metamethod. table must be a table; index may be any value.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 rawset (table, index, value)\par
\par
Sets the real value of table[index] to value, without invoking any metamethod. table must be a table, index any value different from nil, and value any Lua value.\par
This function returns table.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 select (index, \'b7\'b7\'b7)\par
\par
If index is a number, returns all arguments after argument number index. Otherwise, index must be the string "#", and select returns the total number of extra arguments it received.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 tonumber (e [, base])\par
\par
Tries to convert its argument to a number. If the argument is already a number or a string convertible to a number, then tonumber returns this number; otherwise, it returns nil.\par
An optional argument specifies the base to interpret the numeral. The base may be any integer between 2 and 36, inclusive. In bases above 10, the letter 'A' (in either upper or lower case) represents 10, 'B' represents 11, and so forth, with 'Z' representing 35. In base 10 (the default), the number can have a decimal part, as well as an optional exponent part (see \'a72.1). In other bases, only unsigned integers are accepted.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 tostring (e)\par
\par
Receives an argument of any type and converts it to a string in a reasonable format. For complete control of how numbers are converted, use string.format.\par
If the metatable of e has a "__tostring" field, then tostring calls the corresponding value with e as argument, and uses the result of the call as its result.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 type (v)\par
\par
Returns the type of its only argument, coded as a string. The possible results of this function are "nil" (a string, not the value nil), "number", "string", "boolean", "table", "function", "thread", and "userdata".\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 coroutine.create (f)\par
\par
Creates a new coroutine, with body f. f must be a Lua function. Returns this new coroutine, an object with type "thread".\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 coroutine.running ()\par
\par
Returns the running coroutine, or nil when called by the main thread.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 coroutine.status (co)\par
\par
Returns the status of coroutine co, as a string: "running", if the coroutine is running (that is, it called status); "suspended", if the coroutine is suspended in a call to yield, or if it has not started running yet; "normal" if the coroutine is active but not running (that is, it has resumed another coroutine); and "dead" if the coroutine has finished its body function, or if it has stopped with an error.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 coroutine.wrap (f)\par
\par
Creates a new coroutine, with body f. f must be a Lua function. Returns a function that resumes the coroutine each time it is called. Any arguments passed to the function behave as the extra arguments to resume. Returns the same values returned by resume, except the first boolean. In case of error, propagates the error.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 coroutine.yield (\'b7\'b7\'b7)\par
\par
Suspends the execution of the calling coroutine. The coroutine cannot be running a C function, a metamethod, or an iterator. Any arguments to yield are passed as extra results to resume.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 This library provides the functionality of the debug interface to Lua programs. You should exert care when using this library. The functions provided here should be used exclusively for debugging and similar tasks, such as profiling. Please resist the temptation to use them as a usual programming tool: they can be very slow. Moreover, several of these functions violate some assumptions about Lua code (e.g., that variables local to a function cannot be accessed from outside or that userdata metatables cannot be changed by Lua code) and therefore can compromise otherwise secure code.\par
\par
All functions in this library are provided inside the debug table. All functions that operate over a thread have an optional first argument which is the thread to operate over. The default is always the current thread.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 debug.getfenv (o)\par
\par
Returns the environment of object o.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 debug.gethook ([thread])\par
\par
Returns the current hook settings of the thread, as three values: the current hook function, the current hook mask, and the current hook count (as set by the debug.sethook function).\par
\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 debug.getmetatable (object)\par
\par
Returns the metatable of the given object or nil if it does not have a metatable.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 debug.getregistry ()\par
\par
Returns the registry table (see \'a73.5).\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 debug.getupvalue (func, up)\par
\par
This function returns the name and the value of the upvalue with index up of the function func. The function returns nil if there is no upvalue with the given index.\par
\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 debug.setfenv (object, table)\par
\par
Sets the environment of the given object to the given table. Returns object.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 debug.setlocal ([thread,] level, local, value)\par
\par
This function assigns the value value to the local variable with index local of the function at level level of the stack. The function returns nil if there is no local variable with the given index, and raises an error when called with a level out of range. (You can call getinfo to check whether the level is valid.) Otherwise, it returns the name of the local variable.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 debug.setmetatable (object, table)\par
\par
Sets the metatable for the given object to the given table (which can be nil).\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 debug.setupvalue (func, up, value)\par
\par
This function assigns the value value to the upvalue with index up of the function func. The function returns nil if there is no upvalue with the given index. Otherwise, it returns the name of the upvalue.\par
\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 debug.traceback ([thread,] [message] [, level])\par
\par
Returns a string with a traceback of the call stack. An optional message string is appended at the beginning of the traceback. An optional level number tells at which level to start the traceback (default is 1, the function calling traceback).\par
}

