{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 This library is an interface to the standard C math library. It provides all its functions inside the table math.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 math.asin (x)\par
\par
Returns the arc sine of x (in radians).\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 math.cosh (x)\par
\par
Returns the hyperbolic cosine of x.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 math.fmod (x, y)\par
\par
Returns the remainder of the division of x by y that rounds the quotient towards zero.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 math.tanh (x)\par
\par
Returns the hyperbolic tangent of x.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 This library is implemented through table os.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 os.clock ()\par
\par
Returns an approximation of the amount in seconds of CPU time used by the program.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 os.difftime (t2, t1)\par
\par
Returns the number of seconds from time t1 to time t2. In POSIX, Windows, and some other systems, this value is exactly t2-t1.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 os.execute ([command])\par
\par
This function is equivalent to the C function system. It passes command to be executed by an operating system shell. It returns a status code, which is system-dependent. If command is absent, then it returns nonzero if a shell is available and zero otherwise.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 os.exit ([code])\par
\par
Calls the C function exit, with an optional code, to terminate the host program. The default value for code is the success code.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 os.getenv (varname)\par
\par
Returns the value of the process environment variable varname, or nil if the variable is not defined.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 os.remove (filename)\par
\par
Deletes the file or directory with the given name. Directories must be empty to be removed. If this function fails, it returns nil, plus a string describing the error.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 os.rename (oldname, newname)\par
\par
Renames file or directory named oldname to newname. If this function fails, it returns nil, plus a string describing the error.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 The package library provides basic facilities for loading and building modules in Lua. It exports two of its functions directly in the global environment: require and module. Everything else is exported in a table package.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 package.loaded\par
\par
A table used by require to control which modules are already loaded. When you require a module modname and package.loaded[modname] is not false, require simply returns the value stored there.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 package.preload\par
\par
A table to store loaders for specific modules (see require).\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 package.seeall (module)\par
\par
Sets a metatable for module with its __index field referring to the global environment, so that this module inherits values from the global environment. To be used as an option to function module.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 string.byte (s [, i [, j]])\par
\par
Returns the internal numerical codes of the characters s[i], s[i+1], \'b7\'b7\'b7, s[j]. The default value for i is 1; the default value for j is i.\par
Note that numerical codes are not necessarily portable across platforms.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 string.dump (function)\par
\par
Returns a string containing a binary representation of the given function, so that a later loadstring on this string returns a copy of the function. function must be a Lua function without upvalues.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 string.find (s, pattern [, init [, plain]])\par
\par
Looks for the first match of pattern in the string s. If it finds a match, then find returns the indices of s where this occurrence starts and ends; otherwise, it returns nil. A third, optional numerical argument init specifies where to start the search; its default value is 1 and can be negative. A value of true as a fourth, optional argument plain turns off the pattern matching facilities, so the function does a plain "find substring" operation, with no characters in pattern being considered "magic". Note that if plain is given, then init must be given as well.\par
If the pattern has captures, then in a successful match the captured values are also returned, after the two indices.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 string.len (s)\par
\par
Receives a string and returns its length. The empty string "" has length 0. Embedded zeros are counted, so "a\\000bc\\000" has length 5.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 string.lower (s)\par
\par
Receives a string and returns a copy of this string with all uppercase letters changed to lowercase. All other characters are left unchanged. The definition of what an uppercase letter is depends on the current locale.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 string.match (s, pattern [, init])\par
\par
Looks for the first match of pattern in the string s. If it finds one, then match returns the captures from the pattern; otherwise it returns nil. If pattern specifies no captures, then the whole match is returned. A third, optional numerical argument init specifies where to start the search; its default value is 1 and can be negative.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 string.rep (s, n)\par
\par
Returns a string that is the concatenation of n copies of the string s.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 string.reverse (s)\par
\par
Returns a string that is the string s reversed.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 string.sub (s, i [, j])\par
\par
Returns the substring of s that starts at i and continues until j; i and j can be negative. If j is absent, then it is assumed to be equal to -1 (which is the same as the string length). In particular, the call string.sub(s,1,j) returns a prefix of s with length j, and string.sub(s, -i) returns a suffix of s with length i.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 string.upper (s)\par
\par
Receives a string and returns a copy of this string with all lowercase letters changed to uppercase. All other characters are left unchanged. The definition of what a lowercase letter is depends on the current locale.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 This library provides generic functions for table manipulation. It provides all its functions inside the table table.\par
\par
Most functions in the table library assume that the table represents an array or a list. For these functions, when we talk about the "length" of a table we mean the result of the length operator.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 table.concat (table [, sep [, i [, j]]])\par
\par
Given an array where all elements are strings or numbers, returns table[i]..sep..table[i+1] \'b7\'b7\'b7 sep..table[j]. The default value for sep is the empty string, the default for i is 1, and the default for j is the length of the table. If i is greater than j, returns the empty string.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 table.insert (table, [pos,] value)\par
\par
Inserts element value at position pos in table, shifting up other elements to open space, if necessary. The default value for pos is n+1, where n is the length of the table (see \'a72.5.5), so that a call table.insert(t,x) inserts x at the end of table t.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 table.maxn (table)\par
\par
Returns the largest positive numerical index of the given table, or zero if the table has no positive numerical indices. (To do its job this function does a linear traversal of the whole table.)\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 table.remove (table [, pos])\par
\par
Removes from table the element at position pos, shifting down other elements to close the space, if necessary. Returns the value of the removed element. The default value for pos is n, where n is the length of the table, so that a call table.remove(t) removes the last element of table t.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 table.sort (table [, comp])\par
\par
Sorts table elements in a given order, in-place, from table[1] to table[n], where n is the length of the table. If comp is given, then it must be a function that receives two table elements, and returns true when the first is less than the second (so that not comp(a[i+1],a[i]) will be true after the sort). If comp is not given, then the standard Lua operator < is used instead.\par
The sort algorithm is not stable; that is, elements considered equal by the given order may have their relative positions changed by the sort.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1250\deff0\deflang1045{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}{\f1\fnil\fcharset238 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\lang1033\f0\fs17 Class used to interface with file.\par
\par
See a samples.\lang1045\f1\par
